-- French Stocks: ArcelorMittal, EADS, Societe Generale, Vivendi
-- B y   S a r a h   J o n e s
-- 2010-11-12T17:10:52Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-11-12/french-stocks-drop-arcelormittal-eads-vivendi-lead-the-cac-40-s-retreat.html
France’s  CAC 40 Index  slid 36.23, or
0.9 percent, to 3,831.12 at the 5:30 p.m. close in Paris. The
benchmark measure dropped 2.2 percent in the week.  The SBF 120
Index  lost 0.9 percent today.  The following is a list of companies whose shares were
active in Paris. Stock symbols are in parentheses.  ArcelorMittal  (MT NA), the world’s largest steelmaker, lost
2.6 percent to 25.3 euros, pacing a global selloff in commodity-
related companies as investors speculated that China will raise
interest rates to rein in inflation.  Credit Agricole SA  (ACA FP) gained 1.7 percent to 11.58
euros.  Natixis SA  (KN FP) increased 1 percent to 4.01 euros and
 Societe Generale SA  (GLE FP) climbed 1.2 percent to 42.41 euros.
Banks advanced in Europe after Irish government bonds gained for
the first day in almost three weeks as Group of 20 leaders held
emergency talks on the nation’s fiscal crisis.       European Aeronautic, Defence & Space Co.  (EAD FP) tumbled
4.5 percent to 18.16 euros after the parent company of Airbus
SAS reported third-quarter earnings that missed estimates. The
company also said last week’s engine blowout on a Qantas Airways
Ltd. A380 will affect deliveries of the plane next year.  Vivendi SA  (VIV FP) dropped 1.8 percent to 20.20 euros
after French daily La Tribune reported that Vivendi’s tax
regime, which allows the company to deduct losses incurred
abroad from its domestic profit, won’t be renewed when it
expires at the end of 2011. The newspaper cited unidentified
people. A spokesman for France’s finance ministry denied the
report.  To contact the reporter on this story:
